One may show that the modular representation is quite special in many
respects, the basic result being the congruence subgroup property
mentioned in the introduction, i.e. that the kernel  of the
modular representation is a congruence subgroup of level 
. One may also show that the conductor  ,
which is equal to the order of the matrix , is bounded by a universal
function of the dimension (= number of primary fields). Moreover,
if we denote by  the projective order of , i.e. the smallest
positive integer such that  is a scalar matrix, then the integer
